  :schema-extension ".kotoba-schema"
  :float-scope-decision
  "Owner-reviewed 2026-07-20: floating-point fields (e.g. entity-specs :coerce
   :float) and effectful primitives (clock/uuid/mutable-store) are explicitly
   OUT of scope for this tranche. A same-day empirical probe against
   kotoba-lang/compiler@86c3b4b (current main, includes the
   2026-07-20 structured-floating-point landing, see
   90-docs/evidence/260720-kotoba-safe-floating-point-plan.edn in
   com-junkawasaki/root) showed float support is real upstream but requires
   explicit checked f64/f32 conversions -- naive int/float mixing
   (`(/ requested 2.0)`) is rejected (`operation has no admitted lowering`).
   The toolchain pin used by every pilot in this batch
   (kotoba@47a83883.../compiler@269846bb.../kotoba-lang@94443462...) predates
   this landing by 44 compiler commits. Advancing the pin and learning the
   checked-conversion API is tracked as separate follow-up work, not blocking
   this tranche."
  :float-scope-followup-20260720
  "Follow-up same day: (1) verified the exact checked-conversion syntax
   against kotoba-lang/compiler@86c3b4b's frontend.cljc -- float literals are
   plain `2.0`; `defn` needs an explicit `:f64` result keyword or it silently
   defaults to `:i64`; conversion is `(i64-to-f64-checked x)` /
   `(f64-to-i64-checked x)`; arithmetic is named ops (`f64-add` `f64-sub`
   `f64-mul` `f64-div` `f64-sqrt` ... and a parallel `f32-*` set), not
   `+`/`-`/`*`//`. (2) Found a real blocker: kotoba-lang/kotoba's own
   `kotoba.runtime/wasm-binary` (the direct/reference WASM emitter -- a
   separate codebase from kotoba-lang/compiler) does not yet implement
   codegen for `f64-*` ops at its own current main
   (ecb805348a1495b7aac19d3e8af8058baee06fb6), so this tranche's
   dual-backend (reference-wasm vs compiler-kir) qualification pattern
   cannot pass for any float-using source regardless of pin choice -- this
   is missing upstream implementation, not a pin or syntax problem.
   (3) kotoba-lang/kotoba PR #387 (commit fbdf4f6a, merged 2026-07-20T05:14,
   found independently of and shortly after this investigation) confirms
   and formalizes both points: it documents the direct-runtime/compiler
   split explicitly, records an evidenced f32 (not f64) direct-runtime
   `main`, and lands `decimal-f64-parse : string -> [:option :f64]` /
   `decimal-f64x3-parse` as the sanctioned safe replacement for
   `Double/parseDouble`-style string coercion -- while explicitly stating a
   polymorphic `as-float` that also silently coerces numbers/booleans with
   an implicit fallback (exactly this cohort's `main.cljc` `as-float`
   shape) is deliberately NOT provided; callers must decode into a typed
   Variant/Option and match explicitly. Net: this tranche's decision to
   keep float out of scope remains correct after this update -- porting
   `as-float` verbatim would require a real behavior change (drop the
   implicit multi-type coercion and 0.0 fallback), not just a pin bump."}
